vensimInput.name: Population Scenario
vensimInput.description: EnROADS projects the impact of varying rates of future population growth. The default setting of 2.0 corresponds with the the Medium Fertility forecast of the Population Division of the United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs (DESA), which projects world population of 10.9 billion by 2100. A setting of 1.0 corresponds to UN’s Low Fertility forecast (world population of 6.8 billion in 2100) and a setting of 3.0 to the UN’s High Fertility forecast (world population of 16.6 billion in 2100). Values that fall between the Low, Medium, and High forecasts may also be selected.

vensimInput.name: Average Annual Growth in per Capita World GDP
vensimInput.description: Move the slider to control average annual growth of per capital global gross domestic product (GDP). The default value is 2.2 percent, based on 3.0 percent growth over the next three decades, as the emerging economics catch up with the advanced economies, and 1.4 percent for the rest of the century. Average annual growth can vary from 0 to 4 percent. Note that GDP = Population x GDP per Capita.

vensimInput.name: GDP per capita change start year

vensimInput.vensimContextVariable: Annual improvement to energy efficiency of new capital stationary
vensimInput.name: Energy Efficiency of Buildings/Industry
vensimInput.description: In the EnROADS Reference Scenario, energy efficiency increases 1 percent per year, in line with historical trends since the 1970s. EnROADS tracks the aging and replacement of energy-using stationary equipment (buildings and industrial facilities) and mobile equipment (cars, trucks, planes, and ships). Over time, new equipment gradually replaces existing equipment, and moving the slider allows changes the pace of future improvements in the efficiency of the new equipment. A 7 percent annual improvement in efficiency of new equipment will cause a 3.5 percent increase in energy efficiency of the economy overall through 2050, an improvement some experts believe is feasible.

vensimInput.name: Nuclear subsidy $/GJ
vensimInput.description: EnROADS can project the effect of subsidies for low carbon energy technologies. Subsidies are measured in $ per gigajoule (GJ), and the years in which the subsidy starts and ends can be designated. A gigajoule is equivalent to slightly more than 8 gallons of gasoline and nearly 280 kilowatt hours of energy (the latter is roughly the monthly consumption of the average electrified household in the world). Moving the slider to 5 would indicate a subsidy of $5 per GJ and would decrease the cost of the chosen energy source by that much. $6-8 is a sizeable subsidy.

Cost improvement for nuclear
vensimInput.description: What if breakthroughs in research and development (R&D) reduce the cost of low carbon sources of energy suddenly (and not slowly via the learning curve that has traditionally governed reductions in the cost of new technologies)? The number selected in the slider represents the reduction in cost when the breakthrough occurs, that is, 0.6 means a 60 percent decrease. The year of the breakthrough can be specified. The new technology slider allows users to simulate the impact of a radical breakthrough.

vensimInput.name: Carbon price $/ton
vensimInput.description: EnROADS projects the impact of policies that place a price on CO2 emissions, such as a widespread carbon tax or extensive cap-and-trade markets. The price is measured in $ per ton of emissions. A start and end year can be specified, with the price increasing after the start year and growing linearly to the full price over the designated time. A typical coal fired power plant emits a ton of CO2 in generating 1000 kilowatt hours of electricity (4 months of consumption for the average electrified household in the world), and burning 100 gallons of gasoline emits just under a ton of CO2. Some Scandinavian countries now have an emissions price of $20-30/ton, and some experts call for prices of well over $75.

vensimInput.vensimContextVariable: Percent CH4 leakage from natural gas
vensimInput.name: Methane leakage %
vensimInput.description: The simulation can project the impact of actions that reduce the percentage of natural gas leaking into the atmosphere during production and distribution. Default value of 3 percent is based on studies by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, which estimated 2.8 percent leakage. High value of 10 percent is based on 2012 estimates of 9 percent leakage.

vensimInput.name: Accelerated retirement of coal-fired power plants %
vensimInput.description: China has accelerated retirement of old coal plants in recent years, and the simulation can project the impact of doing this on a worldwide basis. Each percentage increase adds to the annual rate of retirement. A boost of 5 percent would be significant.

vensimInput.vensimContextVariable: Target percent below BAU of LULUCF
vensimInput.name: Land use emissions reduction %
vensimInput.description: EnROADS can project the impact of reductions in land use, land use change, and forestry (LULUCF) emissions and in non-CO2 greenhouse gases, sometimes called the short-term forcers, which include methane, N2O, and the F-gases. The start year and target year when reductions are fully achieved can be specified, with a 10-year phase-in period assumed. Note that these are not absolute reductions, but are measured relative to the reference scenario.

vensimInput.vensimContextVariable: Target percent below BAU of other GHGs
